data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort` to kill work exceeding a deadline. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires.
            task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Unwrap any exception thrown inside work()
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

## Key changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` — cooperative |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` + `ResetAbort` | Removed entirely |
| Manual `error` variable | `task.IsFaulted` / `task.Exception` |

## Critical pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** If `work()` is a long-running CPU loop that never checks the token, it will keep running on a thread pool thread even after the timeout fires. To fix this, pass `CancellationToken` into the delegate:

   ```csharp
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       var token = cts.Token;
       var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
       // ... same pattern
   }
   ```

   Then the work must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints.

2. **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted.** If `work()` calls `socket.Receive()` or `Thread.Sleep()`, the token won't interrupt it. Replace with async overloads (`await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token)`) or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead of `Thread.Sleep`.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds a timer internally — leaking it leaks the timer. Always use `using`.

4. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party library, native call) cannot be cancelled with a token. The only option is to move it to a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout.

5. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** except at the top-level orchestration point. The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures only timeout-caused cancellations are caught, not unrelated ones.
